"1350–1410":"1350–1410","1305–1357":"1305–1357","1310–Female":"1310–Afdød","1350":"1350","1305":"1305","Abt 1350":"omkring 1350","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1410":"1410","about 1325":"omkring 1325","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","about 1350":"omkring 1350","1328":"1328","England":"England","Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England","Bescot, Staffordshire, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1325–about 1350":"circa 1325–circa 1350","1325–1350":"1325–1350","1320–1350":"1320–1350","1365–Male":"1365–Overleden","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1305–1357":"1305–1357","1310–Female":"1310–Overleden","1350":"1350","1305":"1305","Abt 1350":"circa 1350","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1410":"1410","about 1325":"circa 1325","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","about 1350":"circa 1350","1328":"1328","England":"England","Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England","Bescot, Staffordshire, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1325–about 1350":"about 1325–about 1350","1325–1350":"1325–1350","1320–1350":"1320–1350","1365–Male":"1365–Deceased","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1305–1357":"1305–1357","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1350":"1350","1305":"1305","Abt 1350":"about 1350","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1410":"1410","about 1325":"about 1325","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","about 1350":"about 1350","1328":"1328","England":"England","Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England","Bescot, Staffordshire, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hillary","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin, Ciaran.","English (of Norman origin):","from the Middle English and Old French male or female personal name <i>Hilari(e)</i>, <i>Ilari(e)</i>, and <i>Elari(e)</i>, from Latin <i>Hilarius</i> and <i>Hilaria</i> ‘joyful’ (from Greek <i>hilaros</i>). The Latin name was chosen by many early Christians to express their joy and hope of salvation, and was borne by several saints, including a 4th-century bishop of Poitiers (died 368) noted for his vigorous resistance to the Arian heresy, and a 5th-century bishop of Arles. Largely due to veneration of Saint Hilarius of Poitiers, the name became popular in France in the forms <i>Hilari</i> and <i>Hilaire</i>, and was brought to England by the Norman conquerors. Although quite popular in France, it was only occasionally used in England, where it was confused with the name in 2 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellery","meanings":["variant of   Hillary  .","habitational name from Elleray in Windermere (Westmorland), probably from Old Norse <i>elri</i> ‘alder’ + <i>vrá</i> ‘nook’.","English:"]},{"name":"Gloor","meanings":["Swiss German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Hillier","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Surrey): occupational name for a roofer from Middle English <i>hil(l)ier</i>, <i>hul(li)er</i>, <i>hel(li)er</i> ‘roofer, slater, tiler’, agent nouns from the Middle English verb <i>hil(i)en</i>, <i>hel(i)an</i>, <i>hul(i)en</i> ‘to put a roof on; cover with a roof’.","French: from the personal name <i>Hillier</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Hilaire</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Alario","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Orazio, Carlo, Rocco, Salvatore, Vita, Vitina.","Italian: from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Ilario</i>, from Latin <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  ).","Italian (Sicily): probably a status name from dialect <i>alariu</i> ‘herald’."]},{"name":"Glor","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Hillery","meanings":["English: variant of   Hillary  . This name has long been established in Ireland (Clare)."]},{"name":"Hilaire","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Pierre, Antoine, Chantal, Edeline, Georges, Luc, Maryse, Mimose, Serge, Yolaine.","French and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the personal name <i>Hilaire</i>, French form of   Hillary   1. This surname is most common in Haiti. Compare   Helaire  ."]},{"name":"Hilleary","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Hillary  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Allaire","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Andre, Lucien, Alphonse, Antoine, Armand, Emile, Michel, Pierre, Raoul, Raymonde, Rolande.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Allaire</i>, a variant of <i>Hilaire</i> (see   Hillary  ). Compare   Dallaire  .","History: Jean and Charles Allaire, two brothers from the Poitou region of France, are recorded in Quebec City, QC, in 1662 and 1663, respectively, the years of their marriage. The descendants of one or another brother also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Dallaire</i>, <i>Delair</i>, and <i>Delaire</i>. — Alexandre Allaire, a Huguenot refugee, brought the name from La Rochelle in France to New Rochelle, NY, in 1686, via the West Indies. He is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Hilario","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Julio, Alfredo, Luis, Abelardo, Arturo, Eduardo, Francisco, Juan, Mario, Pedro, Carlos, Cesar.  Portuguese Afonso, Joao.","Portuguese (<b>Hilário</b>) and Spanish: from a personal name ofthe same origin as   Hillary   1."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","juris